"{\n  \"text\": \"Hi everybody. Everything you can perceive that's life is a eukaryot. And that's the plants, the animals, the insects, the fungus, and all those weird in-between creatures at the bottom of the ocean floor. They're basically cells that have a membrane as well as a nucleus inside the membrane full of DNA. This DNA is what defines the function of the cell. So in any particular eukaryot cell, you can cut open the nucleus, look at its DNA, and say, oh, that's the uh toenail of an elephant, or oh, that's the root of an azalea, or something of that nature. You can identify what it is by its DNA. That's it's uh that's how we define it. Now there's a whole nother world that's much older that this eukaryotic world sits on top of, and that's the prokaryotic world. Their cells are made up very differently. Their cells are just a single membrane, no nucleus, and the DNA sits right along the edge of this membrane and goes back and forth into the environment and the cell. It literally takes its DNA and makes it something transient, going back and forth. So when it needs the DNA, or when the DNA better fits the environment, takes it on, and when it no longer fits, because it can only take on so much DNA at once, it will let that DNA go and take on the better fitting DNA. And so it's constantly fitting its environment to itself through the DNA. This is called lateral gene transfer, and it makes the bacteria and the archaea the two components of this world because they have different membranes. Remember, we define things through DNA, and their DNA is so transient that in these cases there's two different types of membranes that we find in this world. So that's how we define them, archaea and bacteria. But the DNA itself, that's a transient thing. So we can give it definitions like lactobacillus or something like this, but these things can quickly change and conditions will change and the bacteria will change right along with it. And this mutation that's constantly occurring to fit the environment is what we sit on top of. Our whole existence, our whole biology is based upon the foundation of these prokaryotes that exist at the less at the simple life forms. But what they're doing is they're fitting our entire world into the environment at a very precise way, in a way that's more complex than we know. DNA is this entire code that they're using that's very complex and they're fitting our environment into us and us into our environment.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hi everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 0.96,\n      \"end\": 2.56,\n      \"duration\": 1.6,\n      \"confidence\": 0.984,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" Hi\",\n          \"start\": 0.96,\n          \"end\": 1.28,\n          \"duration\": 0.32,\n          \"confidence\": 0.991\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 1.52,\n          \"end\": 1.68,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 1.68,\n          \"end\": 2.0,\n          \"duration\": 0.32,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 2.0,\n          \"end\": 2.24,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \".\",\n          \"start\": 2.24,\n          \"end\": 2.56,\n          \"duration\": 0.32,\n          \"confidence\": 0.932\n        }\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Everything you can perceive that's life is a eukaryot.\",\n      \"start\": 2.56,\n      \"end\": 8.48,\n      \"duration\": 5.92,\n      \"confidence\": 0.987,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" E\",\n          \"start\": 2.56,\n          \"end\": 2.72,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ver\",\n          \"start\": 2.72,\n          \"end\": 2.8,\